<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRO FOOTBALL / DAILY REPORT; RAIDERS; SHELL LOOKING AT EVERYTHING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LONNIE WHITE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Looking at different schemes and lineups has been a priority for the Raiders 
during their bye week. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've been accomplishing what we wanted," Coach Art Shell said. "We've taken 
a look at what our tendencies are, along with different things we may have 
gotten away from. We've gone back to some things we did in training camp and 
other things," 
</P>
<P>
 With defensive tackle Willie Broughton returning from an injury and the 
emergence of rookie linebacker Rob Fredrickson, the Raiders worked with 
different lineups this week. Rookie linebacker James Folston and running backs 
Calvin Jones and Jarrod Bunch, who have been inactive so far this season, have 
received more practice time this week. LONNIE WHITE 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA093094-0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 084113 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 30, 1994, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 2; Column 3; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
107 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRO FOOTBALL / DAILY REPORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE SPRINGER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gene Upshaw, executive director of the NFL Players Assn., visited the Raiders' 
El Segundo training headquarters Wednesday to answer player questions about the 
salary cap. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is the first year of the system," he said, "and there are so many 
misconceptions." 
</P>
<P>
 Criticized for accepting a cap system, Upshaw feels vindicated somewhat by the 
similar demands being made by baseball and hockey owners. 
</P>
<P>
 "You can paint stripes on a donkey and call it a zebra," Upshaw said, "but 
it's still a donkey. You can call it revenue enhancement, but it's still (a 
cap). Our guys are playing. We didn't cancel our season." STEVE SPRINGER 
</P>
</TEXT>
