<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; FLORIDA; COURT VOIDS FEE FOR INCOMING CARS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Supreme Court in Tallahassee ruled that it was unconstitutional to charge 
motorists a steep "impact fee" to bring cars into the state, forcing Florida to 
refund $187 million collected over the past three years. About 633,000 
motorists paid the $295-per-car fee since July 1, 1991, when they brought cars 
into Florida and registered them for the first time. Lawmakers passed the 
measure in 1990 to help finance highway construction, claiming the money was 
needed because of the ever-increasing stream of vehicles on Florida's roads. 
