<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: IRVINE; AUTO MAINTENANCE CENTER PLAN REJECTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RUSS LOAR 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Plans for a combination gas station, tuneup shop and carwash were scrubbed by 
the City Council on Tuesday night after nearly 75 residents packed council 
chambers in protest. 
</P>
<P>
 Developer Joel Burnstine maintained his project's design would actually reduce 
the amount of noise and nighttime light to neighbors of the 1.7-acre lot on the 
southwest corner of Michelson and Culver drives.There is now a gas station at 
the site. 
</P>
<P>
 But council members voted 4-0 against the project, overruling the city 
Planning Commission, which had unanimously approved the project on Aug. 4. 
Councilman Barry J. Hammond abstained from voting, citing potential conflict of 
interest because his business involves the service station industry. 
</P>
<P>
 The council vote came after more than an hour of angry comments from residents 
of nearby condominiums and townhomes who said the proposed business was too 
large for the lot and would increase noise and traffic. City planners 
previously granted Burnstine an exemption from new zoning laws in the 
University Park neighborhood that would have required a four-acre lot for his 
proposed business. 
</P>
<P>
 "If they start that kind of density in Irvine, it's all over," said homeowner 
Joe Patrick. "Once you set that kind of precedent, you cannot stop it." 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Greg Smith, who brought the residents' appeal to the council, 
acknowledged that Burnstine had gone to "some fairly incredible lengths" to 
modify his plan to satisfy nearby residents. But residents at the meeting were 
in no mood for compromise, reacting loudly to Burnstine's presentation. RUSS 
LOAR 
</P>
</TEXT>
